b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48239.htm)  [Next](sbe48241.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n37\\. And on account of the impossibility of rulership.\n\nThose who stand outside the Veda arrive through inference at the conclusion\nthat the Lord is a mere operative cause. This being so, they must prove the\nLord's being the ruler (of the material cause) on the basis of observation.\nBut it is impossible to prove that the Lord is the ruler of the Pradhana in\nthe same way as the potter e.g. is the ruler of the clay. For the Lord is\nwithout a body, while the power of ruling material causes is observed only in\nthe case of embodied beings such as potters. Nor may you have recourse to the\nhypothesis of the Lord being embodied; for--as we have shown under I, 1, 3--\nthere arise\n\np. 523\n\ndifficulties whether that body, which as body must consist of parts, be viewed\nas eternal or as non-eternal.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 38. ... as in the case of the organs...](sbe48241.htm)\n\n"